Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=C2=A0
Happy Monday! Hope you all had a great weekend.=C2=A0
It was a good one here at Not Boring HQ. I got to take Dev to his first Six=
ers game =E2=80=93 he made it through the whole thing, we got a W, and the =
Sixers are advancing to the next round. Excitingly, there are now over 200,=
000 smart, curious people here.=C2=A0
Thank you to all of you for making this happen =E2=80=94 I still can=E2=80=
=99t believe that so many of you read and share what I write, and give me f=
eedback to keep making it better. I feel very lucky that I get to do this, =
and I=E2=80=99m more energized than ever to keep upping my game to keep up.=
 So today, we=E2=80=99re going to tackle something I=E2=80=99ve wanted to t=
ackle for a while: an alternative to disruptive innovation and the Innovato=
r=E2=80=99s Dilemma for the very many cases where they=E2=80=99re misapplie=
d.
This whole post, oddly, started as an idea I had for a post called =E2=80=
=9CAmerica & the Innovator=E2=80=99s Dilemma=E2=80=9D in which I was planni=
ng to shoehorn some of the challenges America faces with respect to progres=
s and innovation =E2=80=93 not building nuclear, pushing crypto offshore, N=
IMBYism, and more =E2=80=93 into the Innovator=E2=80=99s Dilemma framework.=
=C2=A0
But after thinking about it for a few minutes, I realized that I was fallin=
g into a common trap, labeling any incumbent=E2=80=99s difficulty of any ki=
nd with new technology of any kind =E2=80=9Cthe Innovator=E2=80=99s Dilemma=
=E2=80=9D when the facts don=E2=80=99t really fit. As I did more mental gym=
nastics, tried to figure out how to say what I wanted to say about the US o=
f A, something struck me:=C2=A0
What=E2=80=99s happening at Google is part of a broader, looser phenomenon =
than the Innovator=E2=80=99s Dilemma, one that applies at a bunch of differ=
ent levels: at the corporate level, where it was born, up to the national l=
evel, and down to the individual level.=C2=A0
America is deeply Positioned, which makes it challenging to innovate and ta=
ke risks the way it used to. That=E2=80=99s a subject for another post.=C2=
=A0
People can be deeply Positioned, too. The more time you=E2=80=99ve spent ge=
tting good at a particular thing, the more you identify with that thing, th=
e more Positioned you are, the better you get at that thing but the harder =
it is to change when the circumstances do, too. Maybe that=E2=80=99s for an=
other post, as well.=C2=A0
Today, we=E2=80=99re going to talk about why Google=E2=80=99s deep Position=
ing in search is an anchor around its neck and how it might come out of thi=
s stronger.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=C2=A0
The Unbearable Heaviness of Being Positioned
Not every new technology is a disruptive innovation and not every challenge=
 to an incumbent presents an Innovator=E2=80=99s Dilemma.=C2=A0
As AI, specifically Large Language Models (LLMs), threatens to eat away at =
Google=E2=80=99s dominant search business, the people who talk about this k=
ind of thing have reached for Professor Clayton Christensen=E2=80=99s famil=
iar frameworks to explain what=E2=80=99s going on.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThis is classic Innovator=E2=80=99s Dilemma,=E2=80=9D they tweet. =
Classic. Just check out the Twitter search for =E2=80=9Cgoogle innovator=E2=
=80=99s dilemma [ https://substack.com/redirect/10bd0ab8-60b4-4f02-9887-651=
1c87bf114?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ].=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
(Narrator: It is not.)
What people are missing in the analysis is that LLMs, and the products like=
