Positioned
Counter-positioning is my favorite concept in business strategy.=C2=A0
Hamilton Helmer, who includes counter-positioning as one of his 7 Powers [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/bb7b70fb-584b-4272-8a12-aa9303831708?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], defines it as=
: =E2=80=9C=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8BA newcomer adopts a new, superior business mod=
el which the incumbent does not mimic due to anticipated damage to their ex=
isting business.=E2=80=9D
In counter-positioning, the new entrant adopts a business model that the in=
cumbent can=E2=80=99t copy without inflicting collateral damage on itself. =
Like Bill in Kill Bill after The Bride touches his chest, if the incumbent =
takes five steps in the new entrant=E2=80=99s direction, they=E2=80=99re de=
ad.=C2=A0
Jiu jitsu is another helpful analogy: successful counter-positioning involv=
es leveraging an opponent=E2=80=99s strengths and movements against them, u=
sing technique and strategy over brute force. Startups can=E2=80=99t win a =
boxing match against an incumbent, but they have a shot in jiu jitsu.
In the book, Helmer spends as much time detailing the reasons that an incum=
bent fails to mimic a counter-positioned upstart as he does describing how =
an upstart can use counter-positioning, but he never gives the incumbent=E2=
=80=99s position a name. That unnamed state is exactly what I think most pe=
ople are trying to say when they say that a company is facing the Innovator=
=E2=80=99s Dilemma, so let=E2=80=99s give it a name.=C2=A0
To be counter-positioned against, a company needs to be Positioned.=C2=A0
Based on the definition of counter-positioning, we can come up with a defin=
ition of Positioning: =E2=80=9CAn incumbent is susceptible to a new, superi=
or business model due to anticipated damage to their existing business.=E2=
=80=9D
This encapsulates some of the challenges an incumbent faces in the Innovato=
r=E2=80=99s Dilemma =E2=80=93 adopting a disruptive technology can hurt exi=
sting customer relationships and divert resources from higher ROI projects =
=E2=80=93 but it=E2=80=99s broader. It covers situations in which an incumb=
ent faces a new business model but not a new technology, situations in whic=
h an incumbent faces new technologies that are just better on all the impor=
tant dimensions, like Uber was for incumbent taxi companies, and situations=
 in which incumbents somehow fail to adopt even sustaining technologies.=C2=
=A0
The more deeply positioned a company becomes, the more susceptible it becom=
es to being counter-positioned against when a superior new technology or bu=
siness model emerges. A company doesn=E2=80=99t have to be actively counter=
-positioned against to be Positioned; becoming more Positioned just increas=
es the potential for counter-positioning.
I want you to imagine the word =E2=80=9CPositioned=E2=80=9D as something th=
at can take on weight and direction.
Companies can be Positioned on two axes:=C2=A0
Depth: from shallow =E2=80=93 a new startup experimenting with products and=
 models =E2=80=93 to deep =E2=80=93 an incumbent with a very profitable bus=
iness and an organization that has grown up around it to protect it at all =
costs.
Diversity: from platform =E2=80=93 many products or a true platform on top =
of which others can build, often platform companies are Positioned on skill=
s vs. any one product =E2=80=93 to product =E2=80=93 the company is Positio=
ned on one core product, even if it offers others (which are often funded b=
y the core product).
Companies that are deeply positioned on one product are the most susceptibl=
e to counter-positioning.=C2=A0
I like the way Gordon Brander describes [ https://substack.com/redirect/ce4=
0c57b-5ed8-41a0-a3c5-871a8fc5b7f6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] the issue:
Reading that, I picturing a medieval army holding the high ground with comf=
ortable tents and lavish meals, dug in, impervious to its enemy=E2=80=99s a=
