e else might eat it.=C2=A0
Relatedly, Arrow=E2=80=99s Replacement Effect also kinda fits here, as Ashw=
in Varma pointed out on Twitter [ https://substack.com/redirect/ab1269d5-aa=
e3-4f71-93c8-6d25e110b87b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:
In 1962, economist Kenneth Arrow wrote Economic Welfare and the Allocation =
of Resources for Invention [ https://substack.com/redirect/457b1e61-d1a1-45=
90-8dd0-7ee198b5fb3b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ], in which he showed that monopolists may underinvest in R&D =
because they are more concerned with maintaining their current market posit=
ion and profits than risking the introduction of innovations that could ren=
der their existing products obsolete.=C2=A0
I actually don=E2=80=99t think this one fits perfectly either =E2=80=93 Goo=
gle invested in R&D, it just didn=E2=80=99t productize the fruits of that r=
esearch in a way that might put the core business at risk.=C2=A0
As I highlighted in Internet Computers [ https://substack.com/redirect/9c16=
e2c8-3bad-4fb2-936c-83ac68f39b85?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Google is so deeply Positioned on search that i=
t=E2=80=99s willing to make its products worse in order to get people to se=
arch more!=C2=A0
Risk is at the heart of Positioning. When companies have more to lose, they=
 tend to become more risk averse. It=E2=80=99s understandable, but companie=
s need to realize that they=E2=80=99re taking a big risk by avoiding taking=
 risks. Byrne Hobart and Tobias Huber explained it well in Against Safetyis=
m [ https://substack.com/redirect/8299d6e0-e30d-41e6-930a-08f675124fec?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9C=
by mitigating or suppressing visible risks, safetyism is often creating inv=
isible or hidden risks that are far more consequential or impactful than th=
e risks it attempts to mitigate.=E2=80=9D The same applies to companies, an=
d it certainly seems to apply to Google.=C2=A0
In one of the more thoughtful and damning former-employee posts of all time=
, The maze is in the mouse [ https://substack.com/redirect/c22d5989-8a77-43=
61-b1ac-5c918b93cca7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (which you should read if you want to viscerally feel how he=
avy being Positioned can be), ex-Googler (Xoogler?) Praveen Seshadri wrote:=
=C2=A0
While two of Google=E2=80=99s core values are =E2=80=9Crespect the user=E2=
=80=9D and =E2=80=9Crespect the opportunity=E2=80=9D, in practice the syste=
ms and processes are intentionally designed to =E2=80=9Crespect risk=E2=80=
=9D. Risk mitigation trumps everything else. This makes sense if everything=
 is going wonderfully and the most important thing is to avoid rocking the =
boat and keep sailing on the rising tide of ads revenue. In such a world, p=
otential risk lies everywhere you look. People act accordingly:
every line of code you change is risk, so put in a ton of processes to ensu=
re that that every code change is perfect at avoiding risk (never mind if i=
t is uninspiring for the user)
anything you launch is risk, so put in a ton of reviews and approvals (lite=
rally 15+ approvals in a =E2=80=9Claunch=E2=80=9D process that mirrors the =
complexity of a Nasa space launch) just to deploy each minor change to a mi=
nor product
any non-obvious decision is risk, so avoid anything that isn=E2=80=99t grou=
p think and conventional wisdom
any change from the way things used to be done is risk, so stick to how it =
was=E2=80=A6
This isn=E2=80=99t the Innovator=E2=80=99s Dilemma. This is a company that =
is so deeply Positioned that it=E2=80=99s paralyzed.=C2=A0
Noam Bardin, the founder and CEO of Waze, said something similar in his 202=
1 post, Why Did I Leave Google, Or Why Did I Stay So Long? [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/712a0db3-47ce-4446-ba7d-0b2ce78c96ea?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] Bardin paints a picture of a=
 company more focused on protecting itself than serving its users. This pos=
t is worth a read too, but his conclusion makes the point succinctly: =E2=
=80=9CThe innovation challenges at Corp-Tech will only get worse as the ris=
k tolerance will go down. Soon, Lawyers > Builders and the builders will ne=
ed to go elsewhere to start new companies.=E2=80=9D
Not all of this is Google=E2=80=99s fault, per se. As Bardin points out, th=
e company faces a lot of regulatory heat. It has to be responsible; it has =
to manage risk. But with this context, it=E2=80=99s not surprising that sev=
en of the eight Google researchers who co-authored Attention is All You Nee=
d [ https://substack.com/redirect/5b49bae6-e8a5-4bbe-8ff3-08fc2435d091?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] have left =
Google to start their own companies.=C2=A0
As a company deepens it Position, it builds a stronger and stronger desire =
to protect the core, and more and more detritus designed to do just that. I=
t becomes risk averse. The rebels who want to build great things leave.
Even when it doesn=E2=80=99t intend to add policies and features and review=
s and all sorts of things that slow it down, those things appear anyway, li=
ke cobwebs on an unused door. The people get better and better at doing thi=
ngs a certain way, and their doing-new-things muscles atrophy. Not to intro=
duce another new concept this late in the game, but the company=E2=80=99s c=
ore capabilities become core rigidities [ https://substack.com/redirect/ece=
a1c77-cd7b-4843-8ca1-e5c346bf78ca?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
The upshot for Google is that it has too much to lose, and that made it a s=
itting duck for counter-positioning. OpenAI introduced one new business mod=
el =E2=80=93 subscription chat that gives answers =E2=80=93 that could eat =
at its market share, and another =E2=80=93 plugins =E2=80=93 that could cru=
sh it entirely.=C2=A0
Google=E2=80=99s challenges, the ones that allowed it to be counter-positio=
ned against in the first place despite the fact that it developed LLMs firs=
t, are internal. OpenAI just took advantage of them.=C2=A0
To whit, this is the company=E2=80=99s mission statement:=C2=A0
To the extent the company put that mission first, above all else, LLMs woul=
d have been the greatest gift possible. Another tool in the information org=
anization, accessibility, and usefulness toolkit. But as of late, it seems =
that the mission has not come first. At best, it=E2=80=99s come second to t=
he search ad business, as you=E2=80=99ll recognize after viewing the result=
s on just a few queries. At worst, it=E2=80=99s further down the list, behi=
nd internal politics and employee career advancement and political correctn=
ess and comfort and a whole bunch of other things that have built up as Goo=
gle has deepened its Position.=C2=A0
Plus, unlike some of its rivals, most of those things have built up around =
one core product, because Google is deeply Positioned in search.=C2=A0
Positioned Products Versus Positioned Platforms=C2=A0
Thus far, we mostly covered the depth of an incumbent=E2=80=99s Position. B=
ut how they=E2=80=99re Positioned matters a great deal too. And it=E2=80=99=
s why Google seems to be the company everyone thinks is most at risk from L=
LMs.
The depth axis on the positioning matrix is fairly intuitive. Roughly, the =
longer a company does something and the better it does that thing, the deep=
er its Positioning. But the other axis, the product/platform axis, is just =
as important for understanding how a company will respond in the face of a =
big technological or business model shift.=C2=A0
Companies closer to the Product end of the axis are more susceptible to cou=
nter-positioning than those closer to the Platform end, because the Platfor=
ms develop capabilities more than they develop any single product. When a n=
ew technology with a new business model emerges, platform companies are mor=
e easily able to incorporate it into their capabilities than a product comp=
any.=C2=A0
Microsoft is the prime example of a platform company, and not just because =
it added some AI to Bing. The company nearly fell victim to the last two bi=
g shifts =E2=80=93 mobile and cloud =E2=80=93 because of its reliance on Wi=
ndows as its core product. Its recent success is instructive for Google.=C2=
=A0
During the Ballmer era, Microsoft made a series of decisions that made it c=
lear that, even though it had always been a =E2=80=9Cplatform company,=E2=
=80=9D that platform, Windows, was the product. In the face of the shift to=
 mobile, it launched Windows Phone. It acquired another victim of the mobil=
e shift: Nokia. Both mobile attempts were flops. As software moved to the c=
loud, Microsoft kept its Office suite off of iOS devices. It named its clou=
d services provider =E2=80=9CWindows Azure.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
By being so deeply Positioned on Windows, Microsoft let Microsoft flounder.=
 Over the 14 years of Steve Ballmer=E2=80=99s tenure from 2000 to 2014, Mic=
rosoft=E2=80=99s stock price dropped 21%.=C2=A0
Within the first months of Satya Nadella=E2=80=99s tenure, Microsoft visibl=
y shifted its strategy. It launched Office for iPad. It renamed the cloud s=
ervice from Windows Azure to Microsoft Azure. In the nine years since Nadel=
la took the reins, it=E2=80=99s become the most strategically savvy of the =
tech giants. Thompson=E2=80=99s The End of Windows [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/037e7977-3384-4540-be23-b1c27bc896a4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is a good read on Microsoft=E2=80=99=
s transformation, but one line that he includes from Nadella=E2=80=99s firs=
t internal strategy memo captures the point well:
More recently, we have described ourselves as a =E2=80=9Cdevices and servic=
es=E2=80=9D company. While the devices and services description was helpful=
 in starting our transformation, we now need to hone in on our unique strat=
egy. At our core, Microsoft is the productivity and platform company for th=
e mobile-first and cloud-first world.
Microsoft was no longer the Windows company. It re-Positioned on being a pl=
atform company that sells enterprises productivity.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s a much more flexible position from which to maneuver through=
 big shifts. When challengers like Zoom and Slack emerge, Microsoft can cop=
y them and sell Teams to its enterprise clients. When new operating systems=
 emerge, Microsoft can sell its software and services through them. When AI=
 took off, Microsoft both partnered with the space=E2=80=99s leading compan=
y and was the quickest of the big tech companies to visibly inject LLM-base=
d products into its software.=C2=A0
From this position, as long as there are enterprises to buy whatever comes =
next, Microsoft will be able to adapt quickly to sell them productivity in =
whatever form it takes. As a result, Microsoft=E2=80=99s stock is up over 6=
50% since Nadella took over, outperforming the Nasdaq by a very wide margin=
=2E=C2=A0
Google, on the other hand, is decidedly a product company. In one of the be=
st pieces of tech writing I don=E2=80=99t know how I hadn=E2=80=99t read un=
til recently (thanks Jeremy Diamond [ https://substack.com/redirect/a8683f9=
d-e69c-4c6d-8507-c307c01c052d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]), Stevey=E2=80=99s Google Platform Rant [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/f3fd8fdf-16f5-4d06-acc1-b59eea519555?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Google engineer Steve =
Yegge shared his strong view that Google was a product company that needed =
to become a platform company. He wrote (emphasis mine):
The problem is that we're a Product Company through and through. We built a=
 successful product with broad appeal -- our search, that is -- and that wi=
ld success has biased us.
This was 12 years ago, but it rings true today.
You should really read it, but my takeaway is that, as a Product Company, d=
eeply Positioned on search, Google believed that it could reliably predict =
what people want and deliver it for them, like it had with search. =E2=80=
=9CYou can't do that. Not really. Not reliably,=E2=80=9D Yegge ranted. He p=
roposed that Google needed to become a true platform company, to open itsel=
f up to the ecosystem, use tools besides ones built for Google, let others =
build on Google, and eat its own dogfood.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CI'm not saying it's too late for us,=E2=80=9D he warned, 12 years =
ago, =E2=80=9Cbut the longer we wait, the closer we get to being Too Late.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Twelve years later, is it too late for Google? Is the company too deeply Po=
sitioned on search to maneuver its way into AI?=C2=A0
I don=E2=80=99t think so, but I think it=E2=80=99s going to take a shift fr=
om Product to Platform.=C2=A0
Organizing the World=E2=80=99s Information
Google is facing an existential threat, if not an Innovator=E2=80=99s Dilem=
ma. Through its entire history, it=E2=80=99s built skills and structures th=
at reinforce its ability to give the best links for any given search query,=
 and to sell ads against those searches. It has become deeply, deeply posit=
ioned in search.=C2=A0
Now that AI=E2=80=99s time has finally come and the battleground is shiftin=
g rapidly, Google=E2=80=99s strengths have become weaknesses. It has a lot =
to lose, and risks losing it all by not taking risks. To survive, it will n=
eed to cut weight, take risks, and move fast.=C2=A0
Just as Microsoft under Nadella shifted from a Windows company to an enterp=
rise productivity company, from a Product to a Platform, Google needs to re=
turn to its mission and shift from a search company to an information organ=
ization company.=C2=A0
Efforts are underway in Mountain View to build AI into everything that Goog=
le does. Larry and Sergey have come back to work on AI. Google launched Bar=
d [ https://substack.com/redirect/30b364be-dbd1-4524-b25b-0f4eb44b855d?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], its somew=
hat weaker ChatGPT competitor. It=E2=80=99s put together a 160 person team =
to work on Project Magi, its efforts to infuse AI into its search product.=
=C2=A0
The good news about being Positioned is that it=E2=80=99s actually somewhat=
 easier to deal with than the Innovator=E2=80=99s Dilemma once a company ac=
knowledges that it=E2=80=99s no longer in a war of position but a war of ma=
neuver. The Innovator=E2=80=99s Dilemma requires companies to take a bet on=
 external factors =E2=80=93 whether or not there will be a market for this =
crappy new thing eventually =E2=80=93 but in the case of AI, there=E2=80=99=
s no doubt about the size of the prize for the winners. The required shift =
is an internal one, a coming-to-grips with the fact that what got you here =
won=E2=80=99t get you there.=C2=A0
Luckily, the Position that Google has built up over the past 25 years gives=
 it a lot of the pieces required to thrive.=C2=A0
Google.com is the most trafficked website in the world. When Attention is A=
ll You Need [ https://substack.com/redirect/35ec34fc-ac4c-49bd-bbd2-ea7ffbb=
684a2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ],=
 that=E2=80=99s an invaluable asset. While ChatGPT and Bing have garnered t=
he early attention, if Google moves relatively quickly, it will provide mos=
t people=E2=80=99s first interaction with LLM-based products.
Just as that volume gives Google the ability to provide better search resul=
ts for the new things people search every day, it might also give Google=E2=
=80=99s LLMs the ability to learn more quickly. It=E2=80=99s a captive data=
 source in a world in which captive data sources matter more than ever.=C2=
=A0
As models become more multi-modal, and as video becomes a bigger part of th=
e AI story, Google=E2=80=99s treasure trove of YouTube videos will be an in=
valuable resource.=C2=A0
Despite losing the authors of the Transformer paper, Google Brain DeepMind =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/677b28cd-d527-4bef-9d8c-bc6500ee3424?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is still one=
 of the most formidable AI research organizations in the world.=C2=A0
Through its advertising business, Google has more relationships with compan=
ies trying to sell products and services than any other company in the worl=
d. If it can shift to become a Platform =E2=80=93 a big shift, to be sure =
=E2=80=93 it has the potential to build a strong competitor to the ChatGPT =
plugins ecosystem while that ecosystem is still in its infancy.=C2=A0
As I wrote, I believe that an Apex Aggregator that takes actions and makes =
purchases on its users=E2=80=99 behalf has the chance to become a bigger bu=
siness than search. No company in the world has proven better at monetizing=
 intent than Google has.=C2=A0
Doing search well is a very hard problem, and no one does it better than Go=
ogle. If it can get its juice back, it can leverage these powerful new AI c=
apabilities to build products that organize the world=E2=80=99s information=
 and make it accessible and useful, even if that sometimes means putting se=
arch ads second.=C2=A0
Of course, Google has a lot of cultural baggage to shed. It may need to suf=
fer from short-term revenue hits. It will need to learn to take big risks a=
gain. But not taking those risks is an even bigger risk: if Google isn=E2=
=80=99t willing to cannibalize itself, others will happily eat it.=C2=A0
The things that got Google here as it became more deeply Positioned in sear=
ch during the war of position have become weights in the war of maneuver. B=
ut they can also be weapons.
Thanks to Dan for editing!=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today! We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 with a Weekly Dose of Optimism.
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

