line;">declared &#8220;code red.&#8221;</a><span> Its search engine was, fo=
r the first time in two decades, in peril.&nbsp;</span></p><p style=3D"colo=
r: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>=
How it got here is a case study in the downsides of being deeply Positioned=
 on one product. Google </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/82d=
6c51e-2083-4b47-8040-d7cc226812d2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoratio=
n: underline;">engineers invented the Transformer architecture</a><span>. T=
he company built its own AI chatbot, LaMDA, that was good enough to convinc=
e at least one Google engineer, Blake Lemoine, that it was </span><a href=
=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/4713d9e0-ef82-4f36-a576-57cfe480db06?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" st=
yle=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">sentient</a><span>. But=
 the company held LaMDA back, concerned about the risk of releasing a produ=
ct that was known to hallucinate (a risk to Google&#8217;s brand around acc=
urate information) and undoubtedly worried about how a bot that gives answe=
rs instead of links would monetize (a risk to Google&#8217;s golden goose).=
 Instead, OpenAI stole the spotlight with ChatGPT, and then again with </sp=
an><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/35ec34fc-ac4c-49bd-bbd2-ea7ffbb=
684a2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" r=
el=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">plugins</a><s=
pan>, a combination that threatens to bring down Google&#8217;s search mono=
poly.&nbsp;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Even Microsoft, another incumbent, an also-=
ran in search with inferior AI capabilities (save its savvy partnership wit=
h OpenAI) was willing to risk its own chatbot, Sydney, saying unhinged thin=
gs. How was Google so slow to react?&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The downsides=
 of being Positioned come in many flavors and from many directions. All of =
the benefits we discussed above have evil (or at least lazy or risk-averse)=
 twins. As Ben Thompson wrote in 2016 in </span><em><a href=3D"https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/d3d7e910-9b56-4877-b1f7-474e5c9bb934?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #4=
04040; text-decoration: underline;">The Curse of Culture</a></em><span>:</s=
pan></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 20px 0=
; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>As with most such things, c=
ulture is one of a company&#8217;s most powerful assets right until it isn&=
#8217;t: the same underlying assumptions that permit an organization to sca=
le massively constrain the ability of that same organization to change dire=
ction. More distressingly, culture prevents organizations from even knowing=
 they need to do so.</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The biggest and m=
ost obvious downside is that </span><strong>Google&#8217;s search ad busine=
ss is just too good to risk</strong><span>.&nbsp;</span></p><p style=3D"col=
or: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Count=
er-positioning works precisely because incumbents aren&#8217;t willing to r=
isk damaging their existing business. It stands to reason that the better t=
hat existing business is, the less willing an incumbent would be to risk it=
=2E The better your Position, the bette=
r target you are for counter-positioni=
ng. And at $225 billion, Google&#8217;s search business is as good as it ge=
ts.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In humans (and companies are made up of humans=
), this idea is known as </span><strong>loss aversion</strong><span>. Intro=
duced by Daniel Kahneman and Amos Tversky, loss aversion is a cognitive bia=
s where people feel the pain of losing something more intensely than the pl=
easure of gaining something of equal value. This leads to risk-averse behav=
ior and a preference for maintaining the status quo. Google&#8217;s positio=
n as a near-monopolist in search means it has too much to lose to risk cann=
ibalizing itself until and unless it becomes clear someone else might eat i=
t.&nbsp;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Relatedly, Arrow&#8217;s Replacement Eff=
ect also kinda fits here, as </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirec=
